@flexiarg math-informal/structural-characterization
@title Structural Characterization
@sigils [▦/形]
@keywords characterization, structure, complete-description, intrinsic, taxonomy
@audience mathematicians, algebraists, structuralists
@tone analytic
@factor Wisdom (paññā)
@family math-strategy/characterization-result
@references [math-informal/exhaustion-as-theorem math-informal/find-the-right-abstraction math-informal/unfold-the-definition]

! conclusion:
  Give a complete intrinsic description of an object — what it is, in terms of
  simpler structures or invariants — rather than asserting properties about
  it.

  + context: An object (an algebra, a representation, a measure, a group
    action, a category) has been defined or is the focus of attention. The
    paper's contribution is to *say what the object is* in a complete sense:
    as a quotient, as a fibration, as a tensor product, as a module over a
    smaller object, etc. — typically with a uniqueness or universality
    statement.

  + IF:
      You have an object X about which existing results give partial
      information (some properties, some bounds, some examples), and you can
      identify a description of X that is *complete*: another object Y plus a
      construction such that X is exactly built from Y by that construction.

  + HOWEVER:
      Structural characterization differs from `find-the-right-abstraction` in
      direction: that pattern abstracts from many examples to a unifying
      framework; this pattern starts with one object and resolves it into
      simpler components. It also differs from `exhaustion-as-theorem`: that
      lists all instances of a type, this describes one instance fully. Choose
      this leaf when the deliverable is *one* full description, not a list.

  + THEN:
      1. Identify the simpler components from which X can be built (Y plus a
         construction).
      2. Establish the construction rigorously, with whatever
         uniqueness / universality clauses are appropriate.
      3. Verify the structural identification by re-deriving known
         properties of X from the new description.

  + BECAUSE:
      A complete structural description of an object is the strongest
      possible characterization: it lets every property of X be derived from
      properties of Y plus the construction. When such a description exists,
      it is essentially always more useful than a list of properties, because
      it tells you why the properties hold.

  + NEXT-STEPS:
      next[Identify the simpler structure Y and the construction that yields X.]
      next[State the structural identity precisely (with uniqueness / universal property).]
      next[Re-derive known properties of X from the identification.]
